{{Other people}}
'''John C. York''' (born April 18, 1949) is a retired [[Americans|American]] cancer research pathologist, married to [[Denise DeBartolo York|Marie Denise DeBartolo York]], and former co-owner and current co-chairman of the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref name=SFGateFamilyBusiness>[http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/The-Family-Business-49ers-owner-talks-of-her-3302990.php San Francisco Gate: "The Family Business / 49ers owner talks of her brother, her privacy and her priorities" by Nancy Gay] September 1, 2000</ref> The Yorks have four children: sons Jed and Tony, and daughters Jenna and Mara.<ref name=SFGateFamilyBusiness />

==Career==
York was born in [[Muskogee, Oklahoma]]. The son of John Clement York,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=York&GSiman=1&GScid=53310&GRid=155093302&|title=Dr John Clement York (1913-1964) - Find A Grave...|website=findagrave.com}}</ref> a dentist who died when York was 15, York grew up in Little Rock and attended local schools until college. He graduated from the University of Notre Dame in South Bend in 1971.<ref name="ND Alum">{{cite web | url=http://www.nd.edu/aboutnd/notable-alumni/ | title=Notable Alumni | publisher=[[University of Notre Dame]] | accessdate=2009-07-04 }}</ref> He received a doctorate in blood pathology from Stritch School of Medicine at [[Loyola University Chicago]] in 1975, and engaged in seven years of post-doctoral study, specializing in the laboratory diagnosis of lymphoma and leukemia.

York left academia to establish DeYor Laboratories in [[Boardman, Ohio]]. In 1993, he sold DeYor Laboratories to [[Corning Inc.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.49ers.com/team/front-office-roster/john-york|title=Biography|publisher=49ers|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref> York has made a number of contributions in the medical field, having given a $1.5 million contribution to establish an Endowed Chair in Pathology and an Endowed Chief Residency in Pathology at the [[University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences]]. In 1999, he donated a science and math building to [[Catholic High School for Boys]], his alma mater. He also joined [[Jerry Jones]] and an anonymous donor in donating $10 million to the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arktimes.com/ArkansasBlog/archives/2013/10/10/little-rock-catholic-high-gets-10-million-gift-from-jerry-jones-john-york-and-anonymous-donor|title=Little Rock Catholic High gets $10 million gift from Jerry Jones, John York and anonymous donor|last1=Brantley|first1=Max|publisher=Arkansas Times|access-date=September 9, 2018|date=October 10, 2013}}</ref>

On December 28, 2008 John and Denise York announced that their son, [[Jed York]], would become team president and operating head of the franchise, while they would become co-chairmen responsible for providing resources and maintaining their role of interacting with other owners and NFL executives.<ref name="49ers PR_1">{{cite web | url=http://www.49ers.com/pressbox/news_detail.php?PRKey=5053&section=PR%20News | title=Jed York Named Team President | publisher=[[San Francisco 49ers]] | accessdate=2009-07-04 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212064513/http://www.49ers.com/pressbox/news_detail.php?PRKey=5053 | archivedate=2009-02-12 | df= }}</ref> John continues to serve as chairman of the NFL's International Committee<ref name="49er Media Guide">{{cite web | url=http://prod.static.49ers.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/media-guide/2009/Organization.pdf | title=2009 49ers Media Guide | publisher=[[San Francisco 49ers]] | accessdate=2009-08-31 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and also sits on the league's Audit and Business Ventures Committees.<ref name="49er Media Guide"/>

On 24 May 2018, the York family via [[San Francisco 49ers|49ers Enterprises]] bought shares in English soccer club [[Leeds United]] to become a minority investor, the 49's Enterprises is the business arm of the [[NFL]] side [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref name="49ers-investor">{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/club-news/23401/san-francisco-49ers-enterprises-become-minority-investor|title=San Francisco 49ers Enterprises Become Minority Investor |publisher=Leeds United Football Club|date=24 May 2018 |accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/club/Ownership-structure|title=Ownership structure - Leeds United|author=|date=|website=www.leedsunited.com|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>

